WEBVTT

00:08.617 --> 00:10.227
- We can take you to the
foster home right after this.

00:10.271 --> 00:11.663
- What happened
to Adam and Bess?

00:11.707 --> 00:13.404
- It looks like
they were poisoned.

00:13.448 --> 00:15.580
We thought Adam and Bess
were Julian's parents.

00:15.624 --> 00:17.452
- No, they live
on my property.

00:17.495 --> 00:19.367
They were taking him to
Niagara Falls for the weekend.

00:19.410 --> 00:21.543
- So when she's talking
about where she lived,

00:21.586 --> 00:23.719
it threw you off a little bit.
What was that about?

00:23.762 --> 00:25.503
- It's called Mosswood Grove.

00:25.547 --> 00:29.029
- A classmate of Heather's,
and she got mixed up with them.

00:29.072 --> 00:30.508
We never heard from her again.

00:30.552 --> 00:32.032
- Sophie was saying
those people

00:32.075 --> 00:33.424
are actually really serious.

00:33.468 --> 00:35.165
Whatever they're
doing down there,

00:35.209 --> 00:38.125
I bet it's way more interesting
than anything we do.

00:38.168 --> 00:39.561
- So let's go.

00:39.604 --> 00:41.519
- So when you
talk about the work,

00:41.563 --> 00:43.347
what does that mean, exactly?

00:43.391 --> 00:46.263
- It's easier to experience
than it is to explain.

00:46.307 --> 00:48.787
We all have a shadow.
All the good and bad inside

00:48.831 --> 00:50.398
that we try to hide.

00:50.441 --> 00:52.356
We shine a light
on that shadow.

00:52.400 --> 00:54.054
- The guy, back at the dorms
with the ponytail,

00:54.097 --> 00:55.403
I saw him at the motel

00:55.446 --> 00:57.144
when we went to speak
to the manager.

00:57.187 --> 01:00.495
This whole trip to
Niagara Falls story is a hoax.

01:06.457 --> 01:13.508
♪

01:31.265 --> 01:38.315
♪

01:44.669 --> 01:51.720
♪

01:57.726 --> 02:00.685
Mom?

02:00.729 --> 02:05.168
♪

02:20.575 --> 02:23.578
[cricket chirping,
mosquitoes buzzing]

02:29.932 --> 02:33.805
- Well, this is a treat.
A fellow insomniac.

02:33.849 --> 02:36.460
- It's not quite morning,
is it?

02:36.504 --> 02:38.332
Uh, fresh pot here.

02:38.375 --> 02:40.682
- Excellent.
Thank you.

02:40.725 --> 02:42.292
Is the bed okay?
You comfortable?

02:42.336 --> 02:45.861
- Oh, it's fine.
All good.

02:47.689 --> 02:50.822
- So,

02:50.866 --> 02:54.348
you're wrapping things up
with the case, huh?

02:54.391 --> 02:56.654
- No, not quite.

02:56.698 --> 02:58.743
Uh, we're getting there,
though.

02:58.787 --> 03:02.356
- You pressed charges, though.
- Yep.

03:02.399 --> 03:04.967
- Heather seems like she's got
a good handle on things now,

03:05.010 --> 03:06.621
thanks to you.

03:06.664 --> 03:09.798
You know, I just wanna say,

03:09.841 --> 03:12.453
you shouldn't feel
like you have to stay.

03:12.496 --> 03:14.672
I don't.

03:14.716 --> 03:16.979
- Don't get me wrong,
I love having you here,

03:17.022 --> 03:20.809
but, uh,
I realize that it's, uh,

03:20.852 --> 03:24.682
not exactly fun
for you to be here.

03:24.726 --> 03:28.860
- It's fine.
I'm fine.

03:28.904 --> 03:30.819
It's overdue.

03:30.862 --> 03:34.692
- Still, I just don't
want you to feel obligated.

03:34.736 --> 03:38.653
We'll be fine.

03:38.696 --> 03:42.874
- I'd like to stay a bit
longer, if that's okay.

03:44.876 --> 03:46.878
- Well, all right.

03:46.922 --> 03:48.880
One condition, though.

03:48.924 --> 03:52.580
You gotta go with me to this
Rotary Club social this week.

03:52.623 --> 03:56.627
Give us a chance
to welcome you back home.

03:56.671 --> 04:00.370
- Okay.

04:00.414 --> 04:03.286
- ...In just a moment,
but first, this breaking news.

04:03.330 --> 04:05.462
We're live
at the Rockford Lodge,

04:05.506 --> 04:08.378
where according to sources,
a 13-year-old boy

04:08.422 --> 04:10.772
poisoned the couple
posing as his parents

04:10.815 --> 04:13.731
en route to Niagara Falls.
Now all three

04:13.775 --> 04:16.691
were supposedly members
of Mosswood Grove...

04:16.734 --> 04:20.434
- I keep thinking about
that rock in the barn.

04:20.477 --> 04:22.349
What do you think that's about?

04:22.392 --> 04:24.394
- No idea.

04:24.438 --> 04:26.875
Looked like Stonehenge
or something.

04:28.442 --> 04:29.921
- It's an altar maybe,

04:29.965 --> 04:32.794
or a symbol of something.

04:32.837 --> 04:36.580
- Yeah.

04:36.624 --> 04:39.757
Did you report
any of this to Lidell?

04:39.801 --> 04:41.629
He's gonna want me

04:41.672 --> 04:42.934
to claim this as a win.

04:42.978 --> 04:44.588
- We already have
everything we need.

04:44.632 --> 04:47.417
- I d--no, no.
That Adam Lowry, Bess McTeer,

04:47.461 --> 04:49.027
they were escaping
from something,

04:49.071 --> 04:50.725
and Vera Walker
tried to cover it up.

04:50.768 --> 04:52.901
Julian, they took him
for some reason, so...

04:52.944 --> 04:56.339
- And he murdered them
and confessed to it.

04:56.383 --> 04:57.601
It's also that simple.

04:57.645 --> 04:59.995
- You know it isn't.

05:00.038 --> 05:01.953
When a boy that young kills,

05:01.997 --> 05:04.565
it's really never
just his fault.

05:04.608 --> 05:07.568
Whatever is
going on in Mosswood,

05:07.611 --> 05:11.441
Julian's in the thick of it,
so it's not the time

05:11.485 --> 05:14.401
to stop asking questions.

05:14.444 --> 05:15.880
- I know.

05:15.924 --> 05:17.795
- Like with that
classmate of yours,

05:17.839 --> 05:20.102
the one that joined
Mosswood after you graduated.

05:20.145 --> 05:21.756
What happened there?

05:21.799 --> 05:24.019
- Well, there's nothing there.
It's a lost cause.

05:28.371 --> 05:32.332
- It's a lost cause.

05:32.375 --> 05:35.857
- Okay.

05:37.859 --> 05:39.643
It's Vera Walker.

05:44.866 --> 05:46.650
- What the hell are you
people doing to my son?

05:46.694 --> 05:50.045
- He's 13. He is a child.

05:50.088 --> 05:51.873
Now you wanna
try him as an adult?

05:51.916 --> 05:54.702
- His case is in family court.
- Not anymore it isn't.

05:54.745 --> 05:56.878
What did you tell the DA?
- Nothing.

05:56.921 --> 05:59.359
- After you searched our home,
what did you tell them?

06:00.490 --> 06:01.622
- I didn't tell 'em anything.

06:01.665 --> 06:04.712
Uh... Nothing.

06:04.755 --> 06:06.627
Hello?

06:06.670 --> 06:07.976
♪

06:11.545 --> 06:14.112
- Julian's case is
in criminal court.

06:14.156 --> 06:17.768
♪

06:17.812 --> 06:19.640
- You have the right
to remain silent.

06:19.683 --> 06:21.859
Anything you say can
and will be used against you

06:21.903 --> 06:23.861
in a court of law.

06:23.905 --> 06:25.733
- You don't say
anything to anyone.

06:25.776 --> 06:27.561
- No touching, please.

06:27.604 --> 06:28.866
Put your hands out front.

06:28.910 --> 06:30.520
You have the right
to an attorney.

06:30.564 --> 06:31.869
If you can't afford one,

06:31.913 --> 06:33.523
one will be appointed
to you by the court.

06:33.567 --> 06:36.874
- It's the law.

06:44.491 --> 06:50.540
♪

06:50.584 --> 06:51.933
- Don't look at them.
Just keep your head down.

06:51.976 --> 06:53.717
It's gonna be okay.

06:53.761 --> 06:55.066
- Ma'am, you really gotta give
us some space, please.

06:55.110 --> 06:57.852
- Julian.

06:57.895 --> 06:59.984
- Please, step back.
You can meet us at the station.

07:00.028 --> 07:01.682
- I'll be following
right behind you.

07:01.725 --> 07:04.728
- Watch your head.
- I'll be right behind you.

07:04.772 --> 07:06.469
It'll be okay.
I'll be behind you, okay?

07:06.513 --> 07:08.602
Just breathe.
- Mom.

07:10.038 --> 07:14.129
- I'm right behind you.

07:14.172 --> 07:15.565
What are you doing here?

07:15.609 --> 07:17.698
- I had nothing
to do with this.

07:17.741 --> 07:21.441
I need a second here.
- Mom.

07:26.881 --> 07:28.926
- Hey.

07:28.970 --> 07:32.887
This wasn't supposed to happen.
It's not what I wanted.

07:32.930 --> 07:36.107
But where you're going,

07:36.151 --> 07:38.109
it's not easy.

07:38.153 --> 07:40.503
Mostly, you gotta
keep to yourself.

07:40.547 --> 07:43.506
But not too much.

07:45.943 --> 07:48.163
- Let me have your hand.

07:51.122 --> 07:54.952
You're gonna have
to memorize this number.

07:54.996 --> 07:58.695
You have any trouble, you need
anything, give me a call.

08:00.218 --> 08:03.047
Hey.

08:03.091 --> 08:06.137
You're gonna be all right.

08:18.019 --> 08:24.068
♪

08:27.724 --> 08:29.726
- Stay on the line
and face the front.

08:29.770 --> 08:31.685
- Let's go.

08:34.644 --> 08:36.254
- All right,
hands to your side.

08:36.298 --> 08:39.997
Face the wall.
- In front of you.

08:40.041 --> 08:41.651
- Okay. Next.

08:41.695 --> 08:44.524
- Julian Walker,
for juvie wing.

08:44.567 --> 08:48.136
- Palm, kid.

08:48.179 --> 08:49.833
♪

08:52.967 --> 08:56.231
- You're done.
Go.

08:56.274 --> 08:58.755
- Look straight ahead.

08:58.799 --> 09:05.849
♪

09:12.726 --> 09:15.859
♪

09:15.903 --> 09:19.080
- This is your spot.
No trading, no moving around.

09:19.123 --> 09:21.952
Come on, man, move, move.

09:21.996 --> 09:24.955
This is your spot.
No trading, moving around.

09:24.999 --> 09:32.049
♪

09:39.666 --> 09:46.716
♪

09:53.593 --> 09:57.509
- Heather.
- Hi, Mrs. Calhoun.

09:57.553 --> 09:59.250
Long time.

09:59.294 --> 10:02.645
How you doing?

10:02.689 --> 10:05.474
- Still not used to seeing you
in that uniform.

10:07.476 --> 10:10.653
- Can I bother you
for a minute?

10:10.697 --> 10:13.134
It's about Marin.

10:20.750 --> 10:23.100
Last time we spoke,
you'd gotten a few voicemails

10:23.144 --> 10:24.711
from her and that was it.

10:24.754 --> 10:27.757
- You mean last time
we spoke 12 years ago?

10:30.107 --> 10:31.718
- The calls you got from Marin,

10:31.761 --> 10:33.720
they were from Mosswood,
correct?

10:33.763 --> 10:36.548
- Far as I know.

10:36.592 --> 10:38.463
- Why would
she reach out to me?

10:38.507 --> 10:41.423
You were the friend,
weren't you?

10:41.466 --> 10:44.252
- What's that
supposed to mean?

10:44.295 --> 10:46.646
- We both know what that means,
sweetheart.

10:48.822 --> 10:52.390
No, nothing since then.

10:52.434 --> 10:55.437
Nothing?

10:55.480 --> 10:57.700
- I just think it's
strange all that time

10:57.744 --> 11:01.530
you never tried to find her,
being a cop and all.

11:01.573 --> 11:04.315
- I did.

11:04.359 --> 11:07.275
Looked for her in the police
database, social media.

11:07.318 --> 11:09.843
There was never anything.

11:09.886 --> 11:12.672
I just assumed
she was at Mosswood.

11:12.715 --> 11:15.196
- You two had a falling out,
huh?

11:17.154 --> 11:19.200
- Sort of.

11:19.243 --> 11:22.420
- Marin was always after
what she couldn't have.

11:22.464 --> 11:26.555
Always on the take,
even as a little girl.

11:26.598 --> 11:28.775
I've had my share of that.

11:28.818 --> 11:32.474
People like her,
it's not for me.

11:32.517 --> 11:35.520
Not anymore.

11:39.568 --> 11:41.396
- Would you mind
if I took a look at her room?

11:41.439 --> 11:43.354
- Honestly, honey,
there's not much left.

11:43.398 --> 11:46.314
It's a home office now.

11:46.357 --> 11:50.405
But I have a box of her things,
if you wanna take a look.

11:50.448 --> 11:51.754
- Great.

11:54.801 --> 12:01.851
♪

12:03.853 --> 12:06.551
- Benji, I'm glad you're here.
- I just heard what happened.

12:06.595 --> 12:08.902
- We need the best possible
defense lawyer for Julian.

12:08.945 --> 12:11.774
Someone we know is on our side.

12:11.818 --> 12:15.735
- You want me to dig up
some old contacts?

12:15.778 --> 12:18.825
- I want you to dig up
the old Benji.

12:18.868 --> 12:23.830
♪

12:23.873 --> 12:27.355
- So I'm asking again,
why take Julian Walker

12:27.398 --> 12:28.791
up to adult court?

12:28.835 --> 12:30.967
- Your client is
facing two charges

12:31.011 --> 12:32.490
of murder
in the second degree.

12:32.534 --> 12:34.710
Charges to which
he has already confessed.

12:34.754 --> 12:36.973
- This is a clear
demonstration of bias

12:37.017 --> 12:39.541
against the Mosswood Community.
- I'm not going down that road.

12:39.584 --> 12:40.847
- And the provenance
of that confession

12:40.890 --> 12:41.935
is dubious, to say the least.

12:41.978 --> 12:43.719
- That's for
a judge to decide.

12:43.763 --> 12:46.548
Look,
you're welcome to roll the dice

12:46.591 --> 12:47.897
on that confession
getting tossed,

12:47.941 --> 12:49.551
or we can talk about a deal.

12:55.470 --> 12:57.820
Okay, we're listening.

12:57.864 --> 13:00.388
- Your client's facing
a minimum of 30 years to life

13:00.431 --> 13:02.390
for two counts of murder two.

13:02.433 --> 13:06.481
We're willing to let him serve
both sentences concurrently.

13:06.524 --> 13:08.570
- What would that mean
for Julian?

13:08.613 --> 13:11.007
- Well, if he pleads guilty,
we'll accept the recommendation

13:11.051 --> 13:14.489
of the court.
Anywhere from 15 to life.

13:16.447 --> 13:18.449
You people are insane.

13:18.493 --> 13:20.364
- Be that as it may,

13:20.408 --> 13:23.280
it beats going to trial
with a confession.

13:23.324 --> 13:24.760
♪

13:24.804 --> 13:26.893
No need to decide today.

13:26.936 --> 13:29.243
Take some time.

13:29.286 --> 13:31.985
Meditate on it.

13:32.028 --> 13:33.247
♪

13:33.290 --> 13:36.250
- Thank you.

13:36.293 --> 13:38.556
♪

13:39.644 --> 13:43.387
- Is there any chance
you and I can talk?

13:43.431 --> 13:45.433
- I've been advised
against that by my lawyer.

13:45.476 --> 13:48.392
- I talked to the judge who's
been assigned to the case,

13:48.436 --> 13:51.265
and he's ordered an MHE,

13:51.308 --> 13:53.920
psychological evaluation.

13:56.792 --> 13:58.576
- Well, it's
a diagnostic tool--

13:58.620 --> 14:00.796
It's one or the other.

14:00.840 --> 14:03.625
- I wouldn't say crazy, but
that whole Niagara Falls story,

14:03.668 --> 14:05.888
you giving permission,
that wasn't true, was it?

14:05.932 --> 14:08.543
You knew that that couple
wasn't coming back

14:08.586 --> 14:10.501
to Mosswood with your son.

14:10.545 --> 14:12.939
- You don't have to answer.
- Okay.

14:12.982 --> 14:14.592
Why didn't you report it?

14:14.636 --> 14:16.290
- I've learned that
"to protect and to serve"

14:16.333 --> 14:20.511
doesn't apply to Mosswood.
I have my own resources.

14:20.555 --> 14:22.600
- You don't
contact authorities

14:22.644 --> 14:24.907
even when it's
your own son that's missing.

14:24.951 --> 14:28.606
Look where we are now.

14:28.650 --> 14:29.825
♪

14:29.869 --> 14:32.349
Let's go.

14:35.875 --> 14:37.485
♪

14:37.528 --> 14:40.705
What were they
running away from?

14:40.749 --> 14:42.838
- Adam and Bess
were not saving Julian.

14:42.882 --> 14:44.535
They were abducting him,

14:44.579 --> 14:47.451
but you never thought
to consider that, did you?

14:47.495 --> 14:50.454
Julian was defending himself.

14:50.498 --> 14:56.896
♪

15:17.438 --> 15:19.527
You spent
the whole night there?

15:19.570 --> 15:22.399
- Oh, my God,
you should've stayed.

15:28.492 --> 15:31.060
- No, we just talked.

15:31.104 --> 15:32.888
I'm serious.

15:32.932 --> 15:34.890
I met this woman
and some other people.

15:34.934 --> 15:36.457
It was kind of amazing.

15:38.024 --> 15:40.678
- Yeah, they just wanted
to get to know me.

15:40.722 --> 15:44.117
And we talked about you too.

15:44.160 --> 15:47.729
- Yeah, like, about your mom,
and how evil cancer is,

15:47.772 --> 15:51.385
and how your dad isn't really
dealing with her being gone.

15:53.909 --> 15:55.693
Marin, what the hell?

15:55.737 --> 15:57.739
- They were interested.

15:57.782 --> 16:00.002
We were talking about life
and--and the shit that happens.

16:00.046 --> 16:01.786
I told them all
about my mom too.

16:01.830 --> 16:05.051
- Well, next time keep to your
shit and leave mine out of it.

16:05.094 --> 16:07.836
I think
it'd be really good for you

16:07.879 --> 16:09.446
to just go and talk to them.

16:09.490 --> 16:11.057
You--you never open up
about anything.

16:11.100 --> 16:14.886
Oh, my God.

16:14.930 --> 16:16.888
You're so defensive.

16:16.932 --> 16:20.022
I'm gonna take you back there.
- No way.

16:20.066 --> 16:22.416
Yeah.

16:22.459 --> 16:24.200
They're gonna
open you up.

16:25.767 --> 16:28.204
- Heather Novack's
gonna get real.

16:28.248 --> 16:30.902
- Heather, hon,
time for breakfast.

16:30.946 --> 16:34.080
Oh.
Hey, Marin.

16:34.123 --> 16:35.907
I didn't know you were here.

16:38.780 --> 16:40.216
- Your mom know you
spend the night?

16:40.260 --> 16:43.176
- Does she know
where I am ever?

16:43.219 --> 16:46.788
I'm starving.

16:46.831 --> 16:50.052
- Well, you're in luck.
I've got some pancakes working.

16:50.096 --> 16:53.882
Come on down.

16:56.145 --> 16:58.017
Oh, my God,
did you just see that?

16:58.060 --> 17:02.717
He was so freaked out about us
being in bed together.

17:02.760 --> 17:06.025
- Mm.
Unbelievable.

17:14.772 --> 17:19.081
♪

17:28.917 --> 17:35.880
♪

18:01.254 --> 18:08.304
♪

18:30.761 --> 18:37.768
♪

19:00.226 --> 19:02.532
- Did you get enough
to eat this time?

19:02.576 --> 19:04.839
- I didn't eat the meat,
but they gave me an extra roll.

19:04.882 --> 19:06.406
- Mm.

19:06.449 --> 19:08.799
- There aren't any trees here.

19:08.843 --> 19:10.714
I can't even see any
out of the window.

19:10.758 --> 19:13.543
- I know.

19:13.587 --> 19:16.677
I found out you're gonna have
an interview tomorrow.

19:16.720 --> 19:19.375
A psychologist is going to
ask you questions.

19:19.419 --> 19:22.073
- About you.

19:22.117 --> 19:24.554
Then they'll report
back to the judge.

19:24.598 --> 19:27.427
It's important.

19:29.472 --> 19:31.866
- You remember the Fisher
family from over in Walcott?

19:31.909 --> 19:33.650
- Yeah.
- Of course you don't.

19:33.694 --> 19:37.088
Anyway, Glen's one of them.

19:37.132 --> 19:38.655
They have a big part
of the dairy market

19:38.699 --> 19:40.222
from here to Buffalo.

19:40.266 --> 19:42.093
- Yeah, cows.

19:42.137 --> 19:44.487
I'm really glad
you came out here.

19:44.531 --> 19:47.403
- Welcome.
Hi, there.

19:47.447 --> 19:49.405
Jack Sprat,
here to chew the fat.

19:50.885 --> 19:52.495
You must be Harry.
- Yeah.

19:52.539 --> 19:54.715
- Glen Fisher.
Heard all about you.

19:54.758 --> 19:56.760
Come on in.

19:59.459 --> 20:02.157
- Darling, don't eat all the
chicken, yes, please?

20:02.201 --> 20:04.681
- Gentlemen,
this is Harry Ambrose.

20:04.725 --> 20:07.728
Keller born and bred.
You must know these guys.

20:07.771 --> 20:09.817
- Here we go.
Sheriff.

20:09.860 --> 20:11.253
- Good to see you.
Yeah.

20:11.297 --> 20:12.776
Hey, Chief.
- Detective.

20:15.910 --> 20:17.781
- So, uh, Tom's been telling us

20:17.825 --> 20:20.436
that you've been helping
on the Mosswood case.

20:20.480 --> 20:23.787
- Uh, well, just, uh,
offering advice where I can,

20:23.831 --> 20:25.311
that's all.

20:25.354 --> 20:27.922
- My advice,
heavy metal and tear gas.

20:27.965 --> 20:29.489
Worked at Waco.

20:29.532 --> 20:30.620
- Oh!

20:30.664 --> 20:32.274
- Well,
it's all wrapped up now,

20:32.318 --> 20:33.580
so there's no need to worry.

20:33.623 --> 20:37.148
- Uh, yeah, thanks.

20:37.192 --> 20:39.803
- I was talking to an old buddy
of mine down at Public Works.

20:39.847 --> 20:42.850
A Keller old timer.
And he remembers your family.

20:44.678 --> 20:48.638
- Uh, something about
a--a fire in--at your house.

20:48.682 --> 20:50.640
Bad one.

20:50.684 --> 20:52.860
- Yeah, it's when it
was my mother and I.

20:52.903 --> 20:54.470
Yes.

20:54.514 --> 20:56.298
Hmm.

20:56.342 --> 20:58.387
- Oh, sorry, I didn't--
i--if it's a sore subject,

20:58.431 --> 21:00.737
I'm...
- No, no, no.

21:00.781 --> 21:03.914
It, uh, was an accident.
You know, pot on the stove.

21:03.958 --> 21:05.960
That kind of thing.
- Yeah.

21:06.003 --> 21:10.660
- The kind you think would
never happen at your own place.

21:10.704 --> 21:14.316
- Yeah, that kind.

21:14.360 --> 21:17.319
- I'm sorry.

21:17.363 --> 21:19.365
- You were defending yourself.

21:19.408 --> 21:21.628
♪

21:21.671 --> 21:23.282
You have to tell them
how scared you were,

21:23.325 --> 21:25.284
that's important.

21:25.327 --> 21:29.549
And if they ask about Mosswood,
you don't say anything.

21:29.592 --> 21:31.202
You don't talk about the barn.

21:31.246 --> 21:33.335
You don't talk
about our sessions.

21:33.379 --> 21:34.989
They won't understand.
They'll think there's something

21:35.032 --> 21:38.297
wrong with you.

21:38.340 --> 21:40.647
- What about the detective
with the beard?

21:40.690 --> 21:44.868
- His job is
to send people to jail.

21:44.912 --> 21:47.654
What did he say to you
in the car?

21:47.697 --> 21:53.486
♪

21:53.529 --> 21:56.010
- Nothing.

21:56.053 --> 21:59.622
♪

21:59.666 --> 22:01.755
- You can't trust him.

22:01.798 --> 22:03.713
Remember when you told him
about your dream.

22:03.757 --> 22:05.019
Two days later they--
- It wasn't a dream.

22:05.062 --> 22:06.760
- Julian.
We've been over this.

22:06.803 --> 22:08.544
- I don't wanna lie.
- Julian.

22:08.588 --> 22:11.808
These people
do not understand us.

22:11.852 --> 22:14.637
They would do anything
they can to hurt us.

22:14.681 --> 22:17.640
We don't have a choice.

22:17.684 --> 22:20.904
♪

22:20.948 --> 22:23.603
Okay.

22:30.958 --> 22:34.570
- There you are.

22:37.486 --> 22:41.316
- Head's up, Harry.
High school.

22:44.450 --> 22:48.802
- Well, it's about time
I caught sight of you.

22:48.845 --> 22:52.632
I've heard you're back.

22:52.675 --> 22:56.026
- Hi, Carolyn.
- Hi.

22:56.070 --> 22:59.987
Now, why couldn't you have
had this handsome beard

23:00.030 --> 23:03.425
back when you were
Romeo

23:03.469 --> 23:06.341
- Harry was a bit late
to puberty.

23:06.385 --> 23:09.518
- Hmm, not as I recall.

23:09.562 --> 23:12.956
- You heard it.

23:13.000 --> 23:14.958
How have you been?

23:15.002 --> 23:17.831
- Oh.

23:17.874 --> 23:20.442
- Heard you got divorced.

23:20.486 --> 23:23.750
Did Jack tell you that?

23:23.793 --> 23:25.665
- Well, some of us ask.

23:25.708 --> 23:27.971
Ah.

23:29.538 --> 23:32.541
You still have
that cornered look,

23:32.585 --> 23:36.850
like you're about
to run off again.

23:36.893 --> 23:39.983
- I didn't run off.
I--I didn't, I...

23:40.027 --> 23:42.638
I left.
- That's all right.

23:42.682 --> 23:44.945
I knew what you
were going through.

23:44.988 --> 23:47.687
Hard time.

23:47.730 --> 23:50.690
17 years old.

23:50.733 --> 23:53.432
No siblings.
Your parents gone.

23:53.475 --> 23:58.088
I mean, I--I--how do you know
where to put that pain?

24:06.096 --> 24:13.147
♪

24:14.888 --> 24:16.977
- Mom.

24:17.020 --> 24:23.810
♪

24:27.509 --> 24:29.816
- Harry.

24:29.859 --> 24:31.513
Hey.

24:33.646 --> 24:35.996
You okay?
- Yeah, I'm fine.

24:36.039 --> 24:38.389
- Carolyn said you
just up and walked out.

24:38.433 --> 24:39.695
You sure you're okay?

24:39.739 --> 24:41.175
- Will you stop asking me
that question?

24:41.218 --> 24:43.090
I--yeah, I'm okay.
I'm okay, you're okay.

24:43.133 --> 24:45.527
We're all okay.
- All right. Sorry.

24:45.571 --> 24:48.399
- No--
I told you that I was fine.

24:48.443 --> 24:50.576
- Okay, well, the reason
I keep asking if you're fine

24:50.619 --> 24:52.621
is 'cause you don't seem fine.

24:52.665 --> 24:55.058
And I'm just trying
to be a good friend.

24:55.102 --> 24:58.061
You know, it's not like
you'd tell me, right?

24:58.105 --> 25:01.021
I mean, the last 15 years
have pretty much proven that.

25:03.545 --> 25:07.767
- I'm sorry.

25:07.810 --> 25:10.683
- Look.

25:10.726 --> 25:12.206
Don't worry about it.
It's all right.

25:12.249 --> 25:16.863
- No.

25:16.906 --> 25:18.865
I...

25:18.908 --> 25:20.649
♪

25:20.693 --> 25:22.738
I'm not.

25:26.133 --> 25:28.091
- Pull yourself together.

25:28.135 --> 25:31.138
♪

25:31.181 --> 25:33.488
You're pathetic, you know that?
Yeah, I do.

25:35.272 --> 25:37.448
Wanna get out of here?
Come on.

25:37.492 --> 25:38.928
- Yeah.
- I'll make you some eggs.

25:38.972 --> 25:41.975
♪

25:49.156 --> 25:56.163
♪

26:07.087 --> 26:10.133
- I thought I'd stop by.

26:13.354 --> 26:16.662
If that's okay with you.

26:16.705 --> 26:18.489
- You could just
read the report tomorrow

26:18.533 --> 26:21.188
from your office.

26:21.231 --> 26:23.756
- I'd rather be here.

26:29.588 --> 26:32.155
- And what day comes
after Wednesday?

26:32.199 --> 26:34.636
- Thursday.

26:34.680 --> 26:37.160
- Friday.

26:39.554 --> 26:41.730
- Edgewater Juvenile
Detention Center.

26:41.774 --> 26:44.341
- And do you know
why you're here?

26:44.385 --> 26:46.692
- Because of what happened
to Adam and Bess.

26:46.735 --> 26:49.477
- What happened
to Adam and Bess?

26:49.520 --> 26:53.046
- You already know.

26:56.397 --> 26:57.616
- They passed through death,

26:57.659 --> 27:00.531
and now they're
starting over again.

27:00.575 --> 27:02.011
- Is that what happens
when you die?

27:02.055 --> 27:05.058
You start over?

27:05.101 --> 27:07.408
- In different forms.

27:07.451 --> 27:09.192
We're all mixed together.

27:09.236 --> 27:12.326
Pieces of us.

27:18.158 --> 27:25.208
♪

27:30.605 --> 27:37.612
♪

27:56.762 --> 28:03.769
♪

28:06.728 --> 28:09.122
- I didn't do anything.
Stop. Bullshit.

28:09.165 --> 28:11.428
- You know exactly
what you've been doing.

28:11.472 --> 28:13.692
- Whatever.
- Don't "whatever" me.

28:16.782 --> 28:18.348
- Hi, Mrs. Calhoun.
- Hey.

28:18.392 --> 28:21.438
- Let's go.
- Yeah, all right.

28:34.451 --> 28:36.323
- She called me a slut

28:36.366 --> 28:38.455
for supposedly flirting
with her boyfriend,

28:38.499 --> 28:41.371
and then said
she should've never had me.

28:42.895 --> 28:45.462
- Marin.

28:45.506 --> 28:50.163
Welcome to my day.

28:53.688 --> 28:56.691
- Let's forget about the party.
I'm gonna take you home.

28:58.171 --> 29:01.391
- But you already borrowed
the truck and everything.

29:01.435 --> 29:04.351
- I don't care.

29:04.394 --> 29:07.223
All right?

29:07.267 --> 29:09.704
You're coming home with me.

29:12.751 --> 29:14.796
♪

29:18.757 --> 29:25.764
♪

29:36.339 --> 29:43.390
♪

30:01.843 --> 30:08.763
♪

30:34.049 --> 30:37.618
- I've been reading about your
work on the Cora Tannetti case.

30:39.968 --> 30:43.232
- People tend to make more
of that than they should.

30:43.276 --> 30:47.280
- My impression is that you
went beyond the call for her.

30:47.323 --> 30:49.978
Why did you do that?

30:50.022 --> 30:52.763
- That's just...

30:52.807 --> 30:55.854
I could tell she had a story.

31:05.689 --> 31:08.388
Adam or Bess?

31:08.431 --> 31:11.260
- Bess.

31:11.304 --> 31:14.350
- How do you feel about
what happened to her?

31:19.921 --> 31:22.968
What did you think when
you saw her on the floor?

31:29.800 --> 31:33.326
- It wasn't supposed to hurt.

31:38.374 --> 31:39.941
- No.

31:39.985 --> 31:42.639
Julian.

31:48.689 --> 31:50.647
Yes.

31:50.691 --> 31:53.650
- So why did you
give her the tea?

31:53.694 --> 31:56.436
♪

31:56.479 --> 31:58.786
- I can't exactly just barge
into some mechanic's place

31:58.829 --> 32:00.701
and pull him off the couch
right now, can I?

32:00.744 --> 32:02.485
- I just...

32:02.529 --> 32:06.794
- Want this to be over.
I hate lying to him.

32:06.837 --> 32:09.318
- Okay.
What do you wanna do?

32:09.362 --> 32:11.886
Tell him he's never
going home again?

32:15.890 --> 32:18.371
Because she lied.

32:20.503 --> 32:24.116
- This is just a little delay.

32:24.159 --> 32:27.684
- You're not supposed to lie.

32:32.515 --> 32:35.823
- You sp--you split in two.

32:38.869 --> 32:40.393
♪

32:40.436 --> 32:42.961
- Have you lied
about anything to me?

32:49.010 --> 32:50.881
♪

32:53.754 --> 32:55.930
- Julian.

33:05.157 --> 33:07.463
- Ma'am, no, you are not--
- I need to get in there.

33:07.507 --> 33:08.943
- You are not allowed inside.

33:12.077 --> 33:14.514
- Something set Julian off.
You need me?

33:14.557 --> 33:16.385
- Yeah.
- She's his mother.

33:16.429 --> 33:17.473
- It doesn't matter.
- We need to talk to him.

33:18.866 --> 33:21.086
Julian?

33:21.129 --> 33:23.088
It's okay.
It's okay.

33:23.131 --> 33:26.874
- Detective,
she's not the mother.

33:26.917 --> 33:30.573
♪

33:30.617 --> 33:32.836
- It's all right.

33:41.367 --> 33:44.370
- My friend Marin,
the one who went to Mosswood.

33:44.413 --> 33:47.199
I took your advice and
I followed up with her mom.

33:47.242 --> 33:49.244
She gave me a box
of her things.

33:49.288 --> 33:52.378
She'd read this, over and over
when we were young.

33:52.421 --> 33:54.162
She underlined the things
she loved.

33:54.206 --> 33:58.079
Look what I found.
"Julian."

33:58.123 --> 34:00.386
Ever since the beginning,
every time I look at Julian,

34:00.429 --> 34:04.172
I get this feeling,
like he's familiar.

34:04.216 --> 34:07.349
His eyes,
his expressions sometimes.

34:07.393 --> 34:10.222
It's because he's hers.

34:10.265 --> 34:12.354
- Vera Walker
had a birth certificate

34:12.398 --> 34:14.922
and she submitted it at court.
- I know.

34:14.965 --> 34:17.098
I looked it up at town hall.

34:17.142 --> 34:20.319
Julian was born May of '05,
nine months exactly

34:20.362 --> 34:23.278
after Marin went into Mosswood.
The timeline is perfect.

34:23.322 --> 34:25.628
- So either she was pregnant
before she went in there,

34:25.672 --> 34:27.587
or she got pregnant soon after.

34:27.630 --> 34:31.025
- Yeah, some kind of
initiation ritual or something.

34:31.069 --> 34:33.549
Marin's missing.

34:33.593 --> 34:37.249
She hasn't been seen outside
of Mosswood for over ten years.

34:37.292 --> 34:39.468
She could be dead.

34:39.512 --> 34:42.036
- You're saying maybe something
happened to her at Mosswood,

34:42.080 --> 34:44.430
and Vera took Julian.

34:44.473 --> 34:48.129
- Yeah, something happened.

34:48.173 --> 34:52.264
- It's intriguing,
I'll give you that.

34:52.307 --> 34:55.005
- I can feel it.

34:57.660 --> 35:00.272
- So you were a little more
than classmates?

35:00.315 --> 35:02.622
♪

35:02.665 --> 35:04.580
- We were friends.

35:04.624 --> 35:08.323
You're only following up on her
now after all these years?

35:08.367 --> 35:11.021
♪

35:11.065 --> 35:13.328
- She didn't want me to.

35:13.372 --> 35:20.422
♪

35:22.207 --> 35:24.992
- There's no
father's name here.

35:25.035 --> 35:32.086
♪

35:38.527 --> 35:40.312
- Heather.

35:40.355 --> 35:42.270
How are you?
- Hi, Dr. Poole.

35:42.314 --> 35:45.317
Thanks for letting us come by.
Oh, this is Detective Ambrose.

35:45.360 --> 35:48.058
- Ah, a pleasure.
Thank you, Ms. Fisher.

35:48.102 --> 35:49.190
Goodnight.

35:49.234 --> 35:51.671
- We know it's late, but, uh...

35:51.714 --> 35:53.673
can we sit and talk
for a second?

35:53.716 --> 35:56.719
- Sure.
Uh, in my office, please.

36:01.811 --> 36:04.205
Yes.
Yeah, that doesn't surprise me.

36:04.249 --> 36:07.208
My name's on half the birth
certificates in these parts.

36:07.252 --> 36:09.732
I--I tend to be
the go-to obstetrician that--

36:09.776 --> 36:12.126
well, including
this young lady's, huh?

36:12.170 --> 36:15.042
- Uh, you don't remember
this one specifically?

36:15.085 --> 36:17.131
- Uh, no, I'm sorry.

36:17.175 --> 36:18.828
- There were no
hospital records

36:18.872 --> 36:22.484
for the mother, Vera,
so it had to be a home birth,

36:22.528 --> 36:24.530
at Mosswood.

36:24.573 --> 36:27.620
- Okay, yes, I--I think
I can recall it now.

36:27.663 --> 36:30.623
- So you were the attending
doctor at Julian's birth?

36:30.666 --> 36:32.625
- No, after it.
Not at it.

36:32.668 --> 36:35.367
I was--I was called in
for the paperwork.

36:35.410 --> 36:37.238
- You didn't witness Vera
give birth?

36:37.282 --> 36:38.761
- No.

36:38.805 --> 36:41.416
- Did you run any tests to
confirm she was postpartum?

36:41.460 --> 36:42.852
Was the baby nursing?

36:42.896 --> 36:44.680
- I honestly can't remember.

36:44.724 --> 36:47.466
That--that--that was
a long time ago.

36:51.296 --> 36:54.429
Did you see her there?

36:54.473 --> 36:57.258
- Mm.

36:57.302 --> 36:59.391
I--I can't say that I did.

36:59.434 --> 37:01.654
I mean, there were a number
of people living there.

37:01.697 --> 37:03.395
There still are, I imagine.

37:03.438 --> 37:06.572
- Vera Walker called you
to sign the birth certificate.

37:06.615 --> 37:09.314
Why was that?
Had you been treating her?

37:09.357 --> 37:12.317
- No. Like I said, we're not
crawling with OBs in the area.

37:12.360 --> 37:14.275
- Yeah.

37:14.319 --> 37:17.800
Did you go to Mosswood
at any other time

37:17.844 --> 37:21.239
to treat maybe other members?

37:22.544 --> 37:24.503
- I'm sorry, but what--what
does this have to do

37:24.546 --> 37:26.374
with the present case?

37:26.418 --> 37:29.421
- We need to know.

37:29.464 --> 37:31.423
Did you?

37:33.947 --> 37:36.906
- Let me get my files.

37:36.950 --> 37:41.171
♪

37:41.215 --> 37:44.131
- He didn't actually
see Vera give birth.

37:44.174 --> 37:47.134
It fits.

37:47.177 --> 37:48.570
♪

37:48.614 --> 37:50.398
- Yeah.

37:50.442 --> 37:57.492
♪

38:00.843 --> 38:03.803
Where is he?

38:03.846 --> 38:07.328
♪

38:07.372 --> 38:10.331
- Dr. Poole.

38:10.375 --> 38:17.338
♪

38:26.739 --> 38:29.698
Dr. Poole?

38:29.742 --> 38:36.705
♪

38:36.749 --> 38:38.577
Dr. Poole?

38:43.756 --> 38:45.845
- I didn't hear anyone go
in and out the front door,

38:45.888 --> 38:47.368
so...

38:47.412 --> 38:50.589
- He's still here somewhere.

39:03.863 --> 39:06.822
- Dr. Poole.

39:06.866 --> 39:13.916
♪

39:17.398 --> 39:20.401
Dr. Poole.

39:29.932 --> 39:32.892
Hello.

39:32.935 --> 39:37.766
♪

39:43.859 --> 39:46.993
- Oh, my God.

39:51.301 --> 39:53.347
- We need something.

39:53.391 --> 39:56.045
- Here, put this on.
Hold--hold it tight.

39:56.089 --> 39:57.743
Hold it tight.

40:00.833 --> 40:02.443
- Quiet, quiet.

40:06.969 --> 40:08.449
- No, no, no, no.
No, no, no.

40:08.493 --> 40:11.191
No.
Oh.

40:11.234 --> 40:13.846
Oh.

40:31.254 --> 40:35.041
- I need to show you something.

40:38.610 --> 40:42.483
- I need everybody in bed
right now.

40:42.527 --> 40:45.530
No talking.
No chatting.

40:45.573 --> 40:48.315
Lights out means lights out.

40:48.358 --> 40:50.143
Let's go.

40:50.186 --> 40:57.237
♪

41:01.154 --> 41:08.204
♪

41:09.554 --> 41:13.209
- It's through there.

41:15.951 --> 41:18.388
On the right.

41:28.137 --> 41:35.188
♪

41:42.021 --> 41:44.502
- Holy shit.
